First Impressions
CS
, now also known as CS2, has been a staple in the gaming world for years. I’ve sunk countless hours into this game, and it’s still as thrilling as the first time I played it. If you’re into first-person shooters, this game is a must-try. It’s got everything you’d want: intense gameplay, strategic depth, and a massive community.

Gameplay
The gameplay is where CS
truly shines. You’re either a terrorist or a counter-terrorist, and your objective changes based on the map and mode. Whether it’s planting or defusing bombs or rescuing hostages, every round is packed with adrenaline. The game demands quick reflexes and smart tactics. One wrong move, and you’re done for. It’s this high-stakes environment that keeps you on the edge of your seat.

Graphics and Sound
Even though CS
runs on the older Source Engine, the graphics hold up pretty well. The maps are detailed and have a distinct aesthetic, and the recent updates have only made them better. The sound design is top-notch too. From the crack of a sniper rifle to the footsteps of an enemy creeping up behind you, the audio cues are crucial and add a layer of immersion.

The Community and Competitive Scene
One of the best things about CS
is its community. Millions of players from around the world jump into the game daily, ensuring you always have someone to play with. The competitive scene is massive. Watching pro players in tournaments is just as fun as playing, if not more so. The ranking system is also well-designed, pitting you against players of similar skill levels, which keeps the matches challenging and fair.

What I Love
Addictive Gameplay: The fast-paced, tactical gameplay never gets old. Each match feels like a fresh challenge.
Active Community: There’s always someone online, and the community is passionate about the game.
Frequent Updates: Valve keeps the game fresh with regular updates, new skins, and maps.
What Could Be Better
Steep Learning Curve: It’s not the most newbie-friendly game. Be prepared to die a lot when you first start.
Cheaters: Despite Valve’s efforts, cheating can still be an issue. It’s frustrating when you encounter a hacker.
Outdated Engine: The Source Engine is showing its age. While the game looks good, it doesn’t compare to newer titles in terms of graphics.
Final Thoughts
CS
, or CS2 if you prefer, is a legendary game in the FPS genre. Despite some minor issues, it’s incredibly fun and rewarding. Whether you’re looking to casually play with friends or climb the competitive ranks, this game has something for everyone. If you haven’t tried it yet, you’re missing out on one of the best gaming experiences out there.

CS2, or Carbon Disulfide, is a colorless, volatile liquid with the chemical formula CS₂. It has a distinctive, pungent odor similar to that of rotten eggs or radishes, particularly when impure. The pure form of carbon disulfide, however, has a more pleasant, sweetish smell. CS₂ is highly flammable and has been widely used in various industrial applications due to its unique chemical properties.

Chemical Properties
Carbon disulfide consists of one carbon atom and two sulfur atoms, making it a simple covalent molecule. It has a linear structure with bond angles of 180 degrees. The carbon atom is bonded to each sulfur atom via a double bond, resulting in a resonance structure. This arrangement contributes to the molecule's stability and reactivity.

CS₂ is notable for its high refractive index and its solubility in organic solvents like ethanol, acetone, and benzene. It is only slightly soluble in water, which limits its use in aqueous solutions. The liquid form is denser than water, with a density of approximately 1.26 g/cm³ at 20°C.

These processes typically occur in specially designed furnaces and reactors to ensure the efficient production of CS₂ while managing the associated hazards.

Applications
Carbon disulfide is utilized in various industries due to its solvent properties and reactivity. Key applications include:

Chemical Manufacturing: CS₂ is a precursor to numerous chemicals such as carbon tetrachloride, xanthates (used in mining), and dithiocarbamates (used in pesticides and fungicides).

Viscose Rayon Production: One of the largest uses of CS₂ is in the production of viscose rayon, a type of synthetic fiber. The process involves dissolving cellulose in a sodium hydroxide solution, treating it with CS₂ to form cellulose xanthate, which is then dissolved and spun into fibers.

Rubber Industry: CS₂ is used as a solvent in the production of rubber and as a vulcanizing agent to improve the elasticity and strength of rubber products.

Laboratory Use: Due to its ability to dissolve fats, oils, and resins, CS₂ is employed in various laboratory procedures, including extractions and the preparation of certain reagents.

Pesticides: In agriculture, CS₂ has been used as a fumigant to control insects and pests in stored grains and other agricultural products.

Health and Safety Considerations
While carbon disulfide has many industrial applications, it is also associated with significant health and safety risks. It is highly flammable, with a flash point of -30°C, and can form explosive mixtures with air. Therefore, strict handling procedures and adequate ventilation are essential in environments where CS₂ is used.

Exposure to carbon disulfide can have acute and chronic health effects. Inhalation of high concentrations can lead to symptoms such as dizziness, headache, nausea, and, in severe cases, unconsciousness or death. Chronic exposure has been linked to neurological and cardiovascular effects, including peripheral neuropathy and atherosclerosis. It can also affect the reproductive system and cause liver and kidney damage.

To mitigate these risks, occupational exposure limits have been established in many countries. Personal protective equipment (PPE), such as respirators and protective clothing, is required for workers handling CS₂. Additionally, facilities using CS₂ must have appropriate fire suppression systems and emergency response plans.

Environmental Impact
Carbon disulfide is also an environmental concern. It can evaporate quickly and contribute to air pollution. In the atmosphere, CS₂ is oxidized to carbonyl sulfide (COS) and sulfur dioxide (SO₂), which are implicated in acid rain formation and climate change. Therefore, emissions from industrial sources are regulated, and measures are taken to reduce the release of CS₂ into the environment.

Conclusion
Carbon disulfide is a valuable chemical with diverse applications across multiple industries, particularly in the production of viscose rayon, rubber, and pesticides. However, its use is accompanied by significant health, safety, and environmental challenges. Proper handling, stringent safety protocols, and regulatory compliance are essential to minimize the risks associated with CS₂ while harnessing its industrial benefits.

I've got thousands and thousands of hours in CS:GO, Counter-Strike 2 is even better- the game is beautiful, the addition of individual ranks for each map is a welcome change- although it gets a bit boring playing a single map if you're trying to get global elite, it forces you to really hone your skills on that one map- It's easier to want to learn everything about a map if you're playing it 24/7- where as if you play every map- sometimes It's just too much to handle all at once, so you don't bother at all. It allows you to play with lower ranked friends, or simply have some fun on other maps- without messing with your highest rank. Making games go to 13 wins, rather than 16- makes matches shorter and more digestible. In Australia the queuing times can be brutal- in CS:GO there was many times I waited multiple hours to find a game, with all maps selected- only to give up on it. My longest queue was 3 hours and 40 something minutes, all maps selected- with no matches found. When the games can go to 14 - 16- losing such a close, long game- after queuing that long- kills you a little bit inside. 11 - 13 sucks, but it sucks harder the longer it goes on. Counter-Strike is so good that I play it despite the queues sometimes taking so long- I can't say that for ANY other game. I love this game, forever. The only thing I'm not a fan of is giving the AWP- the weapon I was the best with- 5 bullets- but all things are subject to change, you just have to adapt- get used to the new magazine, or get used to another gun. The ranking system seems a bit rougher when you first get a rank- but it's easy enough to rank up- if you're not meant to be stuck at a certain rank, you won't be- eventually, inevitably- it's only a matter of time, a matter of when- not if. If you're into mucking about with a full lobby of friends, or playing an FPS seriously- Counter-Strike 2 is for you. Even when you play Counter-Strike seriously, it can be hilarious- especially with your mates- you can try your best and have a good laugh at the same time. CS 1 personally was better in my opinion in terms of its overall enjoyment and options available. To elaborate, the game even when it was not free I felt offered more to the user for their buck so to speak (time), then what is offered currently in CS2. Despite the hacker issues CSGO has always had, the introduction of prime did have some hackers stray away, however this without a new anti cheat could not be helped. The game offered a fun (all be it flawed) ranking system, that was very challenging, even borderline rage inducing at time, but that is what made it challenging and different from other competitive shooters. Making every rank up, and the road to it, so fulfilling and enjoyable. Especially when you found a good team to play with. In fact many of my friends I game with to this day I met in a random csgo competitive match. Many players took competitive fairly seriously, and so communication was key, and was often times had in matches, however in CS2 this is not the case, and I'd say the introduction of premier and map specific ranks vs 1 total rank overall, has drastically brought down the player base that it once had and the enjoyment competitive brought. With that most people do not care about their rank or if they lose or win a match, because a point system means each match you will go up or down, but there is no title associated with it, and there is no fun in guessing if you'll get that next rank up or not or de rank. Meaning you always had to play your best because you never knew the outcome. Additionally, because each map has it's own rank most people don't care if they lose a match, because they have several ranks on various ones, and it doesn't really matter. It took away the fun or putting a Q of all the maps and learning them cohesively for your overall rank, vs just one map for 1 rank. With all this in mind, most players iv'e encoutered in all my play time thus far on CS2 do not talk and do not care about the match, making it less enjoyable. And when maps are cared about, and you win, I never feel satisfied or get that wow moment, or the fun I once did, because I see my rank and then I see multiple other ranks, that are lower or higher, not motivating me to push further for my rank, as I now want to get them all to the same level making me care less. The point system in premier is the same way, I know how much I will lose or win, an in any event, it is not the same as a rank, and so when in a game and I see a player with 20k points vs 14k I do not get the same distinction or awe I use to when I would see lets say a MG 2 and a LE in the same game. Moving forward, in CSGO 1 there was a vast amount of public servers always populated, and events going on at certain times that the whole community was invested in, even live matches between teams broad cast from the mane menu people would watch. However in comparison, CS2 feels lacking. Overall the graphics are better, and the game feels fairly good, but CS has never been a game most players play for beauty. With that, I think it is a great game with great promise, however lacks the main component it once had pushing it to be a competitive, fun shooter for those to grind out and improve to go up the ranks, I think with the implementation of a ranking system similar to that of the old CSGO, it could have great promise!

Counter-Strike 2 (CS2) arrived as a surprise successor to the long-standing esports giant Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CS:GO) in 2023. While it retains the core gameplay loop of Counter-Strike, CS2 introduces several changes that create a distinct experience. Here's a breakdown of its strengths and weaknesses:

Pros:

Thrilling Gameplay: CS2 retains the high skill ceiling and tactical depth that Counter-Strike is known for. Competitive matches can be incredibly tense and rewarding, demanding teamwork, precise aiming, and strategic thinking.
Upgraded Visuals: CS2 boasts more detailed maps with improved textures and lighting compared to CS:GO. This creates a more visually immersive experience.
Grenade Rework: Grenades have undergone a rework, with more realistic physics and blast effects. This adds a new layer of complexity and mastery to mastering throws.
Newcomers Might Find it Approachable: While still a challenging game, some argue that CS2 offers a slightly less punishing learning curve compared to CS:GO, potentially attracting new players.
Cons:

Technical Issues: CS2 launched with performance issues like microstuttering and lag, especially on lower-end machines. This can be a significant drawback for some players.
Missing Features: A major criticism is the lack of popular game modes from CS:GO, such as Demolition and Arms Race. This limits the variety for players who enjoyed those modes.
Controversial Monetization: While not a core gameplay element, some find the introduction of cosmetic microtransactions jarring in a traditionally skill-based game like Counter-Strike.
Shifting Away from Classic Feel: Aesthetics and movement feel different in CS2 compared to CS:GO. Veterans might find it less "crisp" and responsive. The lower tick rate compared to CS:GO also affects gameplay feel.
Overall:

CS2 is a solid competitive shooter with the potential to become a major esports title. It offers a fresh coat of paint on the Counter-Strike formula with some interesting tweaks. However, technical issues, missing features, and a debatable monetization model hold it back from reaching the heights of CS:GO  at launch.

Recommendation:

For hardcore CS:GO players, CS2 might not be a must-have due to the technical issues and gameplay changes. However, if you're new to Counter-Strike or intrigued by the visual upgrade and grenade rework, CS2 offers a compelling and challenging experience.  Ultimately, the decision depends on your priorities and preferences within the Counter-Strike universe.

I discovered the setting Raw Mouse Input on/off and for me, not being able to pick up the mouse with no fingers, what this setting did literally changed the way I was able to play and literally accelerated gameplay for me. If I flicked fast in a direction I was able to navigate around maps and aim without having to lift my mouse off the pad. So say if I was turning right it would be a fast flick to right, back to center, fast flick to right again etc. Doing this I could basically do a full 360 within like 3-4 swipes. If i had raw mouse input turned on, that setting negates as it only follows where the mouse moves. It really bummed me out that removing this setting has pretty much ended my entire csgo gaming experience and considering they deleted csgo altogether with the replacement of CS2. I was looking forward to playing the game with friends and I've tried so many different setting to try and replicate what raw mouse input did for me. This game was the only fps game that offered a setting like that and its the only reason I stuck around playing csgo for so many years. It sucks watching all your friends play without you and it sucks feeling like you can no longer enjoy a game that gave you so much joy for so many years. I hope the devs at Valve see this and add the setting back into the game.\n\nI have included a video explaining how I play and why mouse raw is so important for me.
